art 1: The Multi - Language Engine(The Access Layer)
We are building a "Hot-Swappable" language system.The app will detect the user's preference, but we will also add a manual toggle because a senior might have their phone set to Danish (by a relative) but prefer reading Turkish.

Step 1: The Setup Install the standard industry library for this.

    Bash

npm install i18next react - i18next i18next - browser - languagedetector
Step 2: The Configuration(src / i18n.ts) Create this file in your src folder.It tells the app how to behave.

    TypeScript

import i18n from 'i18next';
import { initReactI18next } from 'react-i18next';
import LanguageDetector from 'i18next-browser-languagedetector';

// Import your dictionaries (we'll create these next)
import da from './locales/da.json';
import tr from './locales/tr.json';
import bs from './locales/bs.json';

i18n
    .use(LanguageDetector)
    .use(initReactI18next)
    .init({
        resources: {
            da: { translation: da },
            tr: { translation: tr },
            bs: { translation: bs },
        },
        fallbackLng: 'da', // Default to Danish if confused
        interpolation: {
            escapeValue: false, // React handles safety
        },
    });

export default i18n;
Step 3: The Dictionaries(src / locales /) Create three JSON files.This is where the magic happens.

    src / locales / da.json

JSON

{
    "greeting_morning": "Godmorgen",
        "medication_title": "Din Medicin",
            "blood_pressure_title": "Blodtryk",
                "pain_question": "Har du ondt?",
                    "coffee_toggle_on": "Kaffen er klar!",
                        "coffee_toggle_off": "Giv kaffe?"
}
